    "Any right inverse to f induces a BG-map.",
    "In particular a and b are BG-isomorphic..2.2 SG-maps Proposition 3.2.9 Let a ≡ ( (I, A, (A i))) and b ≡ ( (I, B, (B i))) two p-sites with the same base I.",
    "For any function f ∶ A → B the following are equivalent: (i) f is an SG-map with domain a and codomain b (ii) For any s ∈ P 0 (I)), f (A s) ⊂ B s (iii) For any s ∈ P 0 follows that π a (a) ⊃ s, and consequently π b (f (a)) ⊃ π a (a) ⊃ s. We conclude that f (a) ∈ B s. ◻ Fact 3.2.10 Let f ∶ a → b and g ∶ b → c be SG-maps then g ○ f is an SG-map with domain a and codomain c.Proof: Straightforward ◻ Proposition 3.2.11 Let f ∶ A → B.Then f is an isotopy of a to b if and only if f is a bijective and both f and its inverse are SG-maps.Below we shall define the notion SG-isomorphism which is adapted for the study of political structures (simplicial complexes).",
